# Git: integration branch vs `master` (essential)

Routine work targets the **integration branch** — **`agentdevelop`** by default. Override with environment variable **`AGENT_GIT_BRANCH`** if the team uses another shared branch for multi-agent work. **`master`** tracks what is ready for **production** (or your team merges **`prod`** from **`master`** — follow human release docs).

## Sync before you change anything (multi-agent)

Several agents (and humans) push to the same integration branch. Treat **“get latest”** as **`git fetch`** + **`git pull --rebase --autostash`** on that branch.

| When | Action |
|------|--------|
| **Before the first edit** in a session or agent step (code, task files, changelog) | Run **`./scripts/git-sync-agent-branch.sh`** from the repo root (or equivalent: `git fetch origin`, checkout **`AGENT_GIT_BRANCH`** default **`agentdevelop`**, `git pull --rebase --autostash origin <branch>`). |
| **Before `git push`** | Pull/rebase again on the integration branch so your push is based on the current remote tip. |
| **Orchestrator** | **`agents/laravel-ecommerce-agent-loop.sh`** runs the sync script **at the start of each step** (log reviewer, feature coder, coder, tester, closer, committer). Disable with **`AGENT_GIT_SYNC=0`** only for offline or special cases. |

If sync fails (merge conflict after rebase, no network), **stop** and resolve; do not layer new commits on a stale tree.

## Where to commit and push

1. **Branch:** Check out the integration branch before starting. If it does not exist locally:  
   `git fetch origin && git checkout -b agentdevelop origin/agentdevelop`  
   (adjust names if using **`AGENT_GIT_BRANCH`**.)
2. **Commits:** Make commits on the integration branch (or a short-lived branch that merges back into it first).
3. **Push after work:** **`git push origin <integration-branch>`**. Do **not** routinely push only to **`master`** for normal fixes and features.

## When the integration branch may be merged into `master` (and `master` pushed)

Merge **only** if **at least one** of these holds:

| Trigger | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **~2-hour cadence** | Batch promotion: roughly every **two hours**, integrate tested work into **`master`** and push (human or scheduler — not every single commit). |
| **Big production change** | Large or high-risk change that **must** go live soon: security fixes, payment/order critical paths, migrations that block deploy, or similarly material production impact. State that in the PR/commit message or task. |
| **Urgent / production in issue** | The linked **GitHub issue** (or explicit user instruction) says **urgent**, **hotfix**, **production**, **deploy now**, or equivalent. Prefer label **`production-urgent`** on the issue when applicable. |

If none of the above applies, **stop after pushing the integration branch**; do **not** merge to **`master`**.

## Agents and the committer role

- **Coder / tester / closer:** Work on the integration branch; never assume **`master`** must be updated the same hour.
- **Committer / changelog:** Commit on the integration branch and push it. Merge to **`master`** only per the table above.
- **When the user says “push”** (no other qualifier): push the **integration branch** — if you are on **`master`**, switch back after any allowed promotion.

## Conflicts with other instructions

If anything else suggests “always push **master**” for every change, **this rule wins** for branch choice and promotion timing, except when the **user explicitly** asks to merge or release to production now.
